</li>

<li>
<p>Does the time required for the lead to drop to half its initial concentration depend on the value of the initial lead concentration? 
<answer name='answer8' inline='true'>
<choiceinput>
<choice credit='1'>no</choice>
<choice>yes</choice>
</choiceinput>
</answer>
</p>


</li>


</ol>


<solution>


<ol>

<li>
Since the lead level declines by 11% each week, the change <m>p_{t+1}-p_t</m> must be negative, and <m>a=-0.11</m>.
</li>

<li>
If the lead level declines by 11%, that means after a week, the fraction remaining is <m>1-0.11=0.89</m>.  We set <m>b=0.89</m>.
</li>

<li>
To convert from difference form to function iteration form, we must add <m>p_t</m> to both sides.  
<md>
  <mrow>p_{t+1} - p_t\amp = a p_t</mrow>
  <mrow>p_{t+1}\amp = a p_t + p_t = (a+1)p_t.</mrow>
</md>
To make the right hand side of the last line by <m>b p_t</m>, we need to set <m>b=a+1</m>.
</li>

<li>
<p>The drop from 64 μg/dl  to 32 μg/dl will take one half-life
<me>T_{half} = \frac{\log 0.5}{\log 0.89} \approx <round numberdigits="4">$Thalf</round> \text{ weeks}.</me>
To drop to 10 μg/dl, the lead concentration must drop to a factor of <m>10/64=<round numberdigits="4">$ten_64</round></m> of the initial lead concentration.  The time for this to occur is
<me>\frac{\log <round numberdigits="4">$ten_64</round> }{\log 0.89} \approx <round numberdigits="4">$T_ten_64</round> \text{ weeks}.</me>
</p>

</li>

<li>
<p>The drop from 32 μg/dl to 16 μg/dl will take one half-life, or <round numberdigits="4">$Thalf</round> weeks.
To drop to 5 μg/dl, the lead concentration must drop to a factor of <m>5/32=<round numberdigits="4">$ten_64</round></m> of the initial lead concentration, which is the same factor to go from 64 μg/dl to 10 μg/dl.  The time for this to occur is <round numberdigits="4">$T_ten_64</round> weeks.</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>The amount of lead that is removed from the bloodstream is proportional to the lead concentration (since 11% is removed).  If the lead concentration is higher, then more lead is removed each week.  The result is that the concentration decays exponentially, and the half life is independent of concentration.</p>
</li>


</ol>

</solution>


